    {
        "content": "<p>aha, sure, I think I was just being silly then. Both these things would work. I still wonder why not just have index map into <code>enat</code>? is it that much better to have it into <code>nat</code>?</p>",
        "id": 256390797,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Birkbeck",
        "timestamp": 1633517217
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I've never enjoyed working with <code>enat</code>.</p>",
        "id": 256390989,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1633517328
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know exactly what is wrong about it's API, but I never really look forward to using it</p>",
        "id": 256391027,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1633517362
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Isn't it still the problem that it's not <code>with_top ℕ</code>?</p>",
        "id": 256391091,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1633517397
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One issue is that enat doesn't have a multiplication defined it seems</p>",
        "id": 256391258,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex J. Best",
        "timestamp": 1633517487
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So for this sort of thing (subgroup indices) you've fallen at the first hurdle</p>",
        "id": 256391344,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex J. Best",
        "timestamp": 1633517529
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Uh what</p>",
        "id": 256391412,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1633517574
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"127136\">Alex J. Best</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/Infinite.20.20index.20definition/near/256391258\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>One issue is that enat doesn't have a multiplication defined it seems</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Ahh ok then I take it back, I dont want <code>enat</code> then.</p>",
        "id": 256391415,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Birkbeck",
        "timestamp": 1633517576
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well maybe we should define mul on it, I think the issue is that having both zero and infinity means its impossible to make it a linear_ordered_comm_monoid so all the lemmas you'd have to prove by hand excluding the edge cases anyway. What you really want for values of an index is the non-existing epnat of positive naturals including infinity, but at that point maybe its just easiest to use nat</p>",
        "id": 256392592,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex J. Best",
        "timestamp": 1633518272
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There is a mul on <code>with_top nat</code> though</p>",
        "id": 256392709,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex J. Best",
        "timestamp": 1633518349
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>epnat is just (with_top pnat), no?</p>",
        "id": 256392871,
        "sender_full_name": "Yakov Pechersky",
        "timestamp": 1633518435
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes but I'm not sure that definition will have enough api on its own without some more work going into it?</p>",
        "id": 256392991,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex J. Best",
        "timestamp": 1633518495
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right, building that api is separate from having the right api for subgroup.index</p>",
        "id": 256393291,
        "sender_full_name": "Yakov Pechersky",
        "timestamp": 1633518687
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think that subgroup index being 0 when it's infinite is a good idea -- stuff like \"order of element divides order of group\" works great with this convention. In a parallel universe we wouldn't say \"infinite order\" for elements of a group, we'd say \"order 0\" because \"g has order n\" then means that the ideal of integers <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.61508em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>g</mi><mi>t</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g^t=1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9879959999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7935559999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">t</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> is generated by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> in all cases. There is no math-nice multiplication on <code>enat</code> because what do we do with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0\\times\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>? However \"infinite index is 0\" turns out to be math-nice I think, and well-behaved under multiplication (for example the tower law is true with this convention).</p>",
        "id": 256419243,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1633530065
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there a reason not to work with the underlying <code>cardinal</code>s directly here?</p>",
        "id": 256420457,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1633530517
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or are they worse than <code>enat</code>?</p>",
        "id": 256420485,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1633530530
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I think the order of a group is tightly related to the order of elements. And as Kevin points out, <code>ℕ</code> works very well there.</p>",
        "id": 256420960,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1633530687
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The point is an index of two groups, like the order of a group, cannot actually be 0, so 0 is a great place put the infinite index stuff. Yes we could use cardinals but this would make things more complex and it's not clear whether the payoff is any better because in reality mathematicians do not use cardinals. Cardinals are used for a fine-grained study of the infinite, but most mathematics away from set theory does not need such a fine-grained measure of the infinite, something is either finite or countable or uncountable, and this will do in 99.9% of mathematics (100% of mathematics?) away from foundational questions which are not our main object of concern.</p>",
        "id": 256422683,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1633531347
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example the fact that CH is undecidable is actually very good evidence that it's the wrong question in terms of mainstream mathematics</p>",
        "id": 256423044,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1633531491
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/Infinite.20.20index.20definition/near/256419243\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think that subgroup index being 0 when it's infinite is a good idea -- stuff like \"order of element divides order of group\" works great with this convention. In a parallel universe we wouldn't say \"infinite order\" for elements of a group, we'd say \"order 0\" because \"g has order n\" then means that the ideal of integers <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.61508em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>g</mi><mi>t</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g^t=1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9879959999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7935559999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">t</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> is generated by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span> in all cases. There is no math-nice multiplication on <code>enat</code> because what do we do with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0\\times\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>? However \"infinite index is 0\" turns out to be math-nice I think, and well-behaved under multiplication (for example the tower law is true with this convention).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yeah I think I see why this is a good idea now and I'd rather make miniscule changes to the proofs  instead of making some <code>epnat</code> api.</p>",
        "id": 256424178,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Birkbeck",
        "timestamp": 1633531932
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I agree that <code>with_top pnat</code> would be a natural domain for the index of a subgroup. But this monoid is isomorphic to <code>nat</code> (by identifying <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span> with 0), so you may as well work with <code>nat</code>.</p>\n<p>One way of understanding this isomorphism is that it maps <code>n : nat</code> to the cardinality of <code>zmod n</code> i.e. the index of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n\\mathbb Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>. When you define the order of a group, it's natural to work directly with ideals in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>, and so \"order 0\" makes a lot of sense. But I don't think it makes any immediate sense to say that the index of a subgroup is 0 (the index is a cardinality, not an ideal) -- it's really only justified by the isomorphism <code>with_top pnat = nat</code>.</p>",
        "id": 256472960,
        "sender_full_name": "David Wärn",
        "timestamp": 1633549722
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's not isomorphic to nat as an ordered monoid though, which is why the proof gets a little more annoying than the one Chris posted</p>",
